data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code for .NET 8.

## Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `while (_running)` loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow + cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue execution after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `_workerThread.Abort()` in `Stop()` | Force termination | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `GetNextItem()` — "may block" | Blocking call interruption | Pass token to unblock |

## Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime — it doesn't even work. `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown, so the catch block is dead code. `Thread.ResetAbort()` likewise throws. The fundamental shift is from **preemptive** (runtime injects an exception) to **cooperative** (code voluntarily checks a token).

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);       // pass token for checkpoint checks
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent to the old ThreadAbortException catch:
                // clean up partial work, then exit the loop gracefully.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully.
        // Join replaces the old Sleep+Abort pattern.
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // No force-kill equivalent exists in .NET 8.
        // If the thread hasn't stopped, it means GetNextItem/ProcessItem
        // isn't honoring the token — fix those methods instead.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## What Must Change in the Called Methods

The **critical pitfall**: if `GetNextItem()` blocks on a synchronous call that doesn't check the token, cancellation stalls there. You must thread the token through:

```csharp
// BEFORE: blocks indefinitely with no way to interrupt
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until an item is available
}

// AFTER: unblocks when token is cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}

// If using Thread.Sleep anywhere inside ProcessItem:
// BEFORE:
Thread.Sleep(5000);
// AFTER — token-aware wait:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Token not passed to blocking calls** | `GetNextItem()` "may block" — if you don't pass the token, `Cancel()` won't unblock it and the thread hangs past your 2s join timeout. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` is `IDisposable`; leaking it leaks internal timers. Implement `IDisposable` on the processor. |
| **`catch (OperationCanceledException)` too broad** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter to only catch *your* cancellation, not unrelated ones. |
| **Expecting immediate stop** | Cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem` does 30 seconds of CPU work with no token check, cancellation waits. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive steps inside `ProcessItem`. |
| **No force-kill fallback** | There is no `Thread.Abort` equivalent in .NET 8. If you truly need to kill uncooperative code, move it to a child **process** and use `Process.Kill()`. |
